OK, now I can see the current state. The combined rule is:

```
.bib-row,.bib-row-author{display:flex;gap:.75rem;align-items:baseline;padding:.45rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);font-size:.95rem;line-height:1.5;flex-wrap:wrap}
.bib-row-author .bib-cite{min-width:50%;flex:1}
```

The problem: `flex-wrap:wrap` on `.bib-row-author` means when the backrefs overflow, each one wraps to a new line spanning the full row width. What we need is the backrefs to stay in a right-hand column and wrap *within* that column.

Since the HTML doesn't wrap the backrefs in a container, the cleanest CSS-only fix is to remove `flex-wrap` from `.bib-row-author` specifically and instead let the row's right side overflow naturally as inline content. But we can't do that with a combined selector.

The real fix: split the combined rule so `.bib-row-author` gets different treatment — no flex-wrap, and the backrefs behave as inline-wrapping content within the remaining flex space.

<<<EDIT
target: config/site.css
mode: patch
---
find:
.bib-row,.bib-row-author{display:flex;gap:.75rem;align-items:baseline;padding:.45rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);font-size:.95rem;line-height:1.5;flex-wrap:wrap}
.bib-row-author .bib-cite{min-width:50%;flex:1}
~~~
replace:
.bib-row{display:flex;gap:.75rem;align-items:baseline;padding:.45rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);font-size:.95rem;line-height:1.5;flex-wrap:wrap}
.bib-row-author{display:flex;gap:.25rem .5rem;align-items:baseline;padding:.45rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);font-size:.95rem;line-height:1.8;flex-wrap:wrap}
.bib-row-author .bib-cite{flex-basis:100%;margin-bottom:.15rem}
.bib-row-author .bib-backref{white-space:nowrap}
>>>

This approach: the cite takes the full first line (`flex-basis:100%` forces it onto its own row), and the backrefs wrap together on the line(s) below it — staying compact as inline items rather than stretching across the full width. The tighter gap and slightly increased line-height keep the backref links readable when they wrap across multiple lines.

Yes — if the backrefs were wrapped in a container div, we could do a proper two-column layout where the cite and backrefs sit side by side, the cite always gets at least 50%, and the backrefs wrap within their own column. Something like:

```html
<div class="bib-row-author">
  <span class="bib-cite">Whitehead, A.N. Process and Reality...</span>
  <span class="bib-backrefs">
    <a class="bib-backref" href="...">2-1</a>
    <a class="bib-backref" href="...">3-1</a>
    ...
  </span>
</div>
```

Then the CSS would be straightforward:

```css
.bib-row-author {
  display: flex;
  gap: .75rem;
  align-items: baseline;
  padding: .45rem 0;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
  font-size: .95rem;
  line-height: 1.5;
}
.bib-row-author .bib-cite { flex: 1; min-width: 50%; }
.bib-row-author .bib-backrefs {
  flex-shrink: 1;
  max-width: 50%;
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: .25rem;
  justify-content: flex-end;
  font-family: 'DM Mono', monospace;
  font-size: .75rem;
}
```

The cite never goes below half. The backrefs column takes up to half, and wraps internally — 28 Whitehead links would flow across a few tidy lines in the right column. The two columns would always be balanced in the worst case.

Is this something you'd want me to spec out as a build change? The HTML is generated — I'd need to know where the bibliography builder lives to propose the wrapper.

